Let’s be real: few things are more frustrating than stepping back to admire your freshly painted wall… only to notice streaks, patchy spots, or weird roller marks. Ugh. You tried your best. You even watched a couple of YouTube tutorials. So why does your wall look like it got painted by an enthusiastic toddler?
Don’t worry. We’ve all been there, and the good news is—you can fix it. Here's how to touch up those paint streaks and uneven patches like a pro (or at least make it look like one did it for you).
First, Why Does This Even Happen?
Before we jump into the fix, it helps to understand what causes streaks and uneven coverage in the first place. Usually, it's one of these:
Cheap brushes or rollers – They don’t hold paint well and can leave lines.
Not enough paint on your tool – Dry rolling is a classic streak-maker.
Poor technique – Rolling too fast, not overlapping properly, or going back over half-dry paint.
Skipping primer – Especially on new drywall or going from dark to light colors.
Not letting coats dry completely – Patience, friend.
Now that we’ve diagnosed the drama, let’s fix it.
Step 1: Let It Dry (Like, All the Way)
It might be tempting to jump in with more paint the second you see a streak, but don’t. Let the paint dry completely—at least 4-6 hours, or overnight if you can. Paint changes a lot as it dries. What looks like a streak might level out or look totally different in a few hours.
Step 2: Lightly Sand the Trouble Spots
Grab some fine-grit sandpaper (think 220-grit) and gently sand any obvious streaks, ridges, or roller marks. The goal is to smooth things out, not take off all the paint. Wipe the dust away with a dry cloth or tack cloth before moving on.
Step 3: Touch-Up With the Right Tools
If you're only fixing small areas, a high-quality angled brush can do the trick. For larger spots or full walls, use a decent roller (not the $2 kind) with the right nap for your wall texture:
Smooth walls – ⅜” nap or less
Textured walls – ½” nap or more
Pro tip: Pre-wet your roller with a little water (for latex paint) and spin it out so it’s just damp. This helps the roller absorb paint evenly and avoids dry rolling.
Step 4: Apply Paint Like a Pro
Here’s where the magic happens. Use the "W" or "M" technique to roll paint on in a zig-zag pattern, then fill it in without lifting the roller. Always maintain a wet edge—meaning, don’t let one section dry before you paint the next one right beside it.
Overlap slightly with your previous pass, and don’t press too hard. Let the roller do the work.
Step 5: Let It Dry, Then Assess
Once your touch-up or second coat is dry, take a look. Stand back. Look from different angles. Check it in natural light and artificial light (paint is sneaky). Still streaky? You may need one more coat. It happens. Paint is a process.
Bonus Tips for Next Time
Use a primer, especially if you're painting over a dark color or new drywall.
Don’t skimp on paint quality—cheap paint usually means more coats.
Avoid painting in extreme heat or humidity, which can mess with drying and application.
Roll slowly and evenly, and don’t rush the job just to get it done. Future you will thank you.
Bottom Line
Fixing streaky or uneven paint is totally doable, and honestly, part of the DIY game. Even pros mess up sometimes (they’re just better at hiding it). With a little patience, the right tools, and a steady hand, your wall will be back to looking crisp and smooth in no time.
Now go grab that roller and show those streaks who’s boss.

